flowchart TD
    subgraph Chaotic Cognitive Attractor
      A((State A))
      B((State B))
      C((State C))
      A --> B
      B --> C
      C --> A
      A -.-> C
      C -.-> B
    end

    C --> PT{Phase Transition}
    PT --> S(((Cognitive Singularity)))
    S --> N((Emergent Higher-Dimensional Manifold))
This diagram highlights structural dynamism ‚Äì the ability of a cognitive system to radically reconfigure itself. Initially, the attractor (top cluster) shows high complexity within a confined space (recursion within a bounded range). Pushing the recursion to its limit (following the arrows through many iterations) leads to a sudden rupture (the Phase Transition diamond). The diagram‚Äôs flow then literally breaks out of the original cluster into a singular point, and from there into a new cluster. This visually encodes a dimensional jump: the new manifold is drawn separate from the initial attractor cluster, indicating a leap to a new level of organization. The interactive visualization could allow a viewer to toggle or animate this transition ‚Äì for instance, by gradually increasing a ‚Äúchaos parameter‚Äù until the threshold node activates, then revealing the emergent structure. In essence, we map cognition as an evolving topology: it starts as recursive containment (self-looping within a system) and, under its own emergent pressures, transitions into a new self-instantiated form. The Mermaid diagrams capture this evolution by using nodes and subgraphs that can conceptually morph, demonstrating that cognition is not a fixed graph but a living, self-modifying network of thought.
